const title = "What Are the Signs of Depression in a 12 to 14 Year Old?";
const description = "A practical, evidence-based guide to depression warning signs in children ages 12 to 14. Covers irritability, withdrawal, sleep changes, falling grades, physical complaints, suicidal statements, what is typically developing versus a red flag, and when to talk to your pediatrician or call 988, based on AAP, CDC, and USPSTF guidance.";

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Is it typical that my 12-year-old seems moody all the time?",
    answer: "Some moodiness is common in early adolescence, but persistent irritability, withdrawal, loss of interest in usual activities, sleep changes, or falling grades lasting more than 2 weeks may be signs of depression rather than typical development (AAP, 2022). If your 12-year-old seems stuck in a low or angry mood most days, talk to your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I worry if my 13-year-old wants to be alone more?",
    answer: "Wanting more privacy is typical at ages 12–14, but a 13-year-old who is isolating from friends, family, and activities they used to enjoy may be showing a red flag for depression (AAP, 2022). If the withdrawal is persistent, worsening, or paired with changes in sleep, appetite, or school performance, contact your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "Can depression in early teens look like anger instead of sadness?",
    answer: "Yes. In adolescents ages 12–14, depression often shows up as irritability, anger, or a short temper rather than obvious sadness, which is why it is sometimes missed by adults (AAP, 2022). If your child seems persistently angry, easily overwhelmed, or emotionally flat for more than 2 weeks, talk to your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "Is it typical that my child has stomachaches before school when they are depressed?",
    answer: "Yes, depression and anxiety in 12–14 year olds can show up as physical complaints like stomachaches, headaches, or nausea, especially on school mornings, even when no medical illness is found (AAP, 2022). If these symptoms are frequent, interfere with school, or come with withdrawal or low mood, discuss them with your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "When should I take suicidal statements seriously?",
    answer: "Always take suicidal statements seriously, even if your 12–14 year old says they were joking or being dramatic. The AAP advises that any talk of wanting to die, self-harm, or feeling like a burden needs urgent mental health evaluation (AAP, 2022). Contact your pediatrician immediately, and call or text 988 if there is any immediate safety concern."
  },
  {
    question: "Will my child's pediatrician screen for depression at this age?",
    answer: "Yes. The USPSTF recommends screening all adolescents ages 12 and older for major depressive disorder when systems for accurate diagnosis and follow-up are in place (USPSTF, 2022). If your child has not been screened, you can ask your pediatrician directly for a depression evaluation."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I wait and see if this phase passes?",
    answer: "No. A brief rough week can happen, but symptoms that last more than 2 weeks, worsen, or affect sleep, school, friendships, or safety should not be handled with a wait-and-see approach (AAP, 2022). Early evaluation improves outcomes, so contact your pediatrician if you are concerned."
  }
